data.content:
This code **does not use `Thread.Abort`** — so there's no `Thread.Abort` migration issue here. It uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep`, all of which work fine in .NET 8.

That said, manual `Thread` management is outdated. The idiomatic .NET 8 approach uses `Task` / `Parallel`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Key `Thread.Abort` migration notes** (for when you do encounter it elsewhere):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — **removed** |
| Abort + catch `ThreadAbortException` | Use `CancellationToken` + check `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` |
| Abort as timeout kill | Use `Task.WaitAsync(timeout)` or `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` |

**Pattern for cancellable work:**

```csharp
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

await Task.Run(() =>
{
    foreach (var step in steps)
    {
        cts.Token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        DoWork(step);
    }
}, cts.Token);
```

The cooperative cancellation model (`CancellationToken`) replaces the old forced-abort model entirely.
